messages.content: Didn't know that Yubi HSM protects again double signing, gotta look into that. But KSM alone does not protect from double signing as far as I've tested it
You can run the HSM/TMKMS in a self hosted server with a direct fast connection to you validator cloud server, or just setup the validator as self hosted.

Basically KMS and validator nodes are separate ones (but also HSM can store keys itself on validator node, but preferable to separate them).
Running KMS at home can cause lots of slashes due to many factors (home validating is whole issue). So you can rely on external DC with your own pre-configured baremetal or in any other way put HSM in server USB. If HSM is inserted there are plenty ways and manuals to setup it, no rocket science here. So the main deal is to plug HSM, I think some DC support can effort this if you can order for their address HSM (previously open ticket about this task)

Yes, you're right. Yubi (even 2) didn't have anti double sign feature, at least their few years ago modules and I think no changes here.
By design only Ledger (Nano) can be configured to avoid double sign.
Digging into new decisions, some good signs on the way, maybe software KSM will evaluate to next stage, in fact it's the matter of code.
Or we will come to SGX and just relax and forgot about it 🙈

This is a broad topic but just our 2 cents and hope they're worth for you to take ideas and people discussing on those.

**A** - Centralization:
I think that foundation delegations are a good thing to help non top-10 validators and aliviate centralization, but seems a fact that without those delegations the network is quite centralized and believe that the team should think of ways to fix that.

- As someone said it's not ideal for delegators to stake on a node and in a couple of months need to redelegate to another one because their current validator didn't renew their delegations and lost their seat (also is a problem for validators).
- With such amount of stake in the top validators is hard to attract delegations (they've already got the a big chunk of circulating tokens), so it's quite hard for non top validators to become non dependent on foundation delegations (even harder with the previous point in mind, going in and out the active seat).
- Going out of the active set for months would possibly increase the number of validators getting tired for not getting the expected results and shutting down their infra because they have to stay for months in the bench, and what they've done for the project in previous months becoming worthless.

**B** - Delegation assignments:
I think that team is doing good work on this and counting on the community for taking decissions. Also, is not a simple issue, but some points that could be good IMO:

1.- Having a clear and predictable scoring system (as possible), with different parameters in mind

- complexity of the tasks: some tasks are much more complex and time consuming and with bigger associated costs than others, does a youtuber video score the same as developing a tool or setting up a relayer?
- duration of the delegation for the type of tasks: does developing a complex app/utility get the delegations for the same time that a couple youtube videos or that managing a community? does managing a community make keep you the foundation delegation over time forever? does it maintaining an app or a relayer server?
- if self delegations are part of the scoring system, all accounts (rewards, and coinlist options 1 & 1) should be taken into account, but have in mind that not everyone got the same rewards from testnets, so maybe the % of auto-staked tokens would be the most fair meassure than just the net amount.
- if commission rate is part of the scoring, should be clear how this would impact on the scoring, because commission it's key also for attracting delegations

2.- About attracting delegations, I think this is good for the Umee project, but seems like kind of abstract and cheatable meassure. How does someone prove that attracted delegations? Only clear messaging on chats? Wouldn't the work put on websites, blog posts, telegram and discord channels, achievements, etc. attract delegations indirectly?

**TL;DR;**
Think like these 2 topics (centralization and delegation) are very important for the network, but I would prioritize on decentralization meassures/actions. It's kinda sad seeing validators with lots of million tokens earning hundreds of thousands dollars a month, while very valuable validators have to compete working hard to achieve the foundation delegation and survive in the active set, or in the future leaving the project even though they were OG's and helped the project flourish. So, taking meassures to help redistribute users delegations into non top validators should be a great strategy to achieve a healthy network and community IMHO.
